The paper focuses on the development and evaluation of a tactile sensor for robotic manipulation tasks, which falls under the field of robotics (cs.RO). The sensor uses multiple micro-cameras and image processing techniques to detect multi-directional deformations of a gel-based skin, which involves computer vision (cs.CV) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) methods. The evaluation of the sensor's capabilities involves the use of deep convolutional neural networks, which falls under the field of machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the paper also discusses the potential applications of the sensor in state estimation problems, which is relevant to the field of control systems (cs.SY).
